parts:
Great question. Here’s exactly what we’re changing—and why—so GTM no longer competes with your LCP/FCP but still captures pageviews reliably.

---

# What we add/modify (page code)

## 1) Replace the default GTM loader in `<head>` with a **scheduled loader**
- We **keep** `dataLayer` and the early `gtm.start` event (so GTM can process a “page view” when it finally loads).
- We **defer** the network request for `gtm.js` until *after* the page has painted—either on `load` → `requestIdleCallback` (safe default), or after the **LCP** has rendered (more aggressive).

### Safe default (recommended to start)
```html
<!-- Keep your preconnect if you already have it -->
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://www.googletagmanager.com" crossorigin>

<script>
  // buffer dataLayer events as usual
  window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  window.dataLayer.push({ 'gtm.start': Date.now(), event: 'gtm.js' });

  function loadGTM() {
    var s = document.createElement('script');
    s.async = true;
    s.src = 'https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtm.js?id=GTM-KKDQNKRP';
    document.head.appendChild(s);
  }

  // Load GTM after onload, then on idle (fallback to short timeout)
  window.addEventListener('load', function () {
    (window.requestIdleCallback || function (cb) { setTimeout(cb, 600); })(loadGTM);
  });
</script>
```

### More aggressive (load **after LCP** renders)
This fires GTM as soon as the browser reports the (final) LCP entry, with fallbacks so you don’t miss hits if LCP never fires (rare) or the user bounces early.

```html
<script>
  window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  window.dataLayer.push({ 'gtm.start': Date.now(), event: 'gtm.js' });

  function loadGTM() {
    if (loadGTM._done) return; loadGTM._done = true;
    var s = document.createElement('script');
    s.async = true;
    s.src = 'https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtm.js?id=GTM-KKDQNKRP';
    document.head.appendChild(s);
  }

  // 1) Prefer loading right after LCP is known
  (function () {
    var armed = false;
    if ('PerformanceObserver' in window) {
      try {
        var po = new PerformanceObserver(function (list) {
          // any LCP entry is good enough to stop competing with it
          if (!armed) { armed = true; loadGTM(); }
          po.disconnect();
        });
        po.observe({ type: 'largest-contentful-paint', buffered: true });
      } catch (e) { /* noop */ }
    }
    // 2) Fallbacks so we don’t miss pageviews
    window.addEventListener('load', function () {
      // if LCP didn’t arrive by load, give the page a tiny breather and go
      setTimeout(loadGTM, 400);
    });
    // 3) Absolute last resort (early bounces)
    setTimeout(loadGTM, 2500);
  })();
</script>
```

> Keep the **`<noscript>`** iframe in `<body>` unchanged. It only runs for JS-disabled users; it won’t affect your LCP path for normal users.

---

## 2) (Optional but smart) Consent stub before GTM
If you use Consent Mode or want to be explicit about defaults, add a tiny **gtag stub** *before* GTM. This just pushes to `dataLayer`; it doesn’t fetch anything by itself.

```html
<script>
  window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){ dataLayer.push(arguments); }
  // Example defaults; adjust to your policy
  gtag('consent', 'default', {
    ad_storage: 'denied',
    analytics_storage: 'granted',
    wait_for_update: 500
  });
</script>
```

This lets Consent Mode work correctly even though GTM itself loads later.

---

# What we change (inside GTM Container)

When you delay GTM, **some built-in triggers may have already passed** (e.g., DOM Ready, Window Loaded). To keep everything firing as expected without pulling GTM forward again:

1) **Use “All Pages (Page View)”** or a **Custom Event** trigger rather than “DOM Ready” / “Window Loaded” for your essential tags (GA4 config/page_view, etc.).  
   - “All Pages” fires on the `gtm.js` event you already queued in `dataLayer`. It will run as soon as GTM loads.
   - If you want explicit control, also push a custom event before loading GTM:
     ```html
     <script>window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || []; dataLayer.push({event: 'initial_page_view'});</script>
     ```
     Then, in GTM, switch core tags to trigger on **Custom Event = `initial_page_view`**.

2) **De-prioritise heavy tags**  
   - Move ads/remarketing/heatmap pixels off “All Pages” and onto **“Window Loaded”** *or* a **Custom Event** like `after_interaction`. (Those won’t block rendering and won’t fire until the user engages.)
   - Use **Tag Sequencing**: ensure GA4 Config precedes other GA4 events if you split them.

3) **Container hygiene**  
   - Disable unused tags and variables, and consolidate triggers to avoid duplicate firings.
   - Prefer server-side tagging later if you want the best perf + privacy posture.

---

# Why this helps (and trade-offs)

- **Perf**: GTM’s network and execution happen *after* your hero image and critical CSS render, so LCP/FCP are not contending for bandwidth/CPU.
- **Measurement**: Pageviews still fire (on the queued `gtm.js` or `initial_page_view`), just **later**. You *may* lose very short bounces that exit before your chosen delay—tune the fallback timings (`600–1200 ms` is a good starting band).
- **Stability**: By avoiding `DOM Ready` / `Window Loaded` triggers for core measurement, you’re not depending on GTM being present before those events.

---

# Quick checklist for you

- [ ] Replace the head snippet with **one** of the two loaders above (default or LCP-aware).  
- [ ] (Optional) Add the **consent stub**.  
- [ ] In GTM, switch essential tags to **All Pages (Page View)** or **Custom Event: `initial_page_view`**.  
- [ ] Move heavy/marketing tags off “All Pages” to **Window Loaded** or custom engagement events.  
- [ ] Verify in **GTM Preview**: you should see `gtm.js` (or `initial_page_view`) only *after* page load/LCP, and your tags firing from that event.  
- [ ] Verify in **DevTools → Network**: `gtm.js` request begins after `load`/idle (or after LCP, if you used the LCP variant).

If you want, we can also wire the **LCP-aware** loader now and leave a single constant at the top (e.g., `const GTM_DELAY_MS = 600;`) so you can tune the fallback without touching the logic.

How about this?

---

   (() => {
      const GTM_ID = 'GTM-XXXXXXX';
      let loaded = false;

      const loadGTM = () => {
        if (loaded) return;
        loaded = true;
        const s = document.createElement('script');
        s.async = true;
        s.src = `https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtm.js?id=${GTM_ID}`;
        s.referrerPolicy = 'origin';
        document.head.appendChild(s);
      };

      if ('PerformanceObserver' in window && 'largest-contentful-paint' in PerformanceObserver.supportedEntryTypes) {
        const observer = new PerformanceObserver((entryList) => {
          const entries = entryList.getEntries();
          if (entries.length) {
            observer.disconnect();
            loadGTM();
          }
        });
        observer.observe({ type: 'largest-contentful-paint', buffered: true });
      }

      window.addEventListener('load', () => setTimeout(loadGTM, 0));
      setTimeout(loadGTM, 5000); // ultimate fallback
    })();

That’s close! Two must-fixes and a couple of refinements:

## 1) You must initialize `dataLayer` **and** push the canonical bootstrap event **before** loading GTM
The official snippet pushes `{ event: 'gtm.js', 'gtm.start': Date.now() }` so that when GTM boots it immediately processes a Page View-type event. Without this, some tags configured on “All Pages (Page View)” may not fire as expected.

## 2) Prefer loading right **after LCP is effectively finalized**, with sane fallbacks
Use the LCP observer, but:
- capture the **last** entry seen (not just “any” entry),
- disconnect and fire after `load` or when the page becomes hidden (common way to finalize LCP),
- keep an idle/timeout fallback so you don’t miss short visits.

Here’s a drop-in version of your snippet with those fixes (keep your `<noscript>` iframe unchanged):

```html
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://www.googletagmanager.com" crossorigin>

<script>
(() => {
  const GTM_ID = 'GTM-XXXXXXX';

  // 1) Prep dataLayer and queue the canonical bootstrap event
  window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  window.dataLayer.push({ 'gtm.start': Date.now(), event: 'gtm.js' });

  let loaded = false;
  const loadGTM = () => {
    if (loaded) return;
    loaded = true;
    const s = document.createElement('script');
    s.async = true;
